                            "If you reward your team for success, they will try to do more things like whatever it was that got them the reward. So, be careful about what you measure, and be careful what you reward. Get it wrong, and your team will probably fail. This all seems obvious, but in truth, it's pretty complicated. The reason is that the way most leaders define success misses one of the most important points. If you measure people only on outcomes, they will do whatever it takes to avoid negative outcomes. They'll play it safe and fall back on whatever they already know that works. They'll keep giving you exactly what you've always gotten, nothing more or less. The thing is, avoiding a negative outcome is not a great measure of success. Avoiding negative outcomes doesn't lead to greatness. On the other hand, if you want people to work really hard, reward them for that. If you want people to take risks, try new things, and come up with new ways of doing things, incentivize them for their effort. Those things don't always lead to what we think of traditionally as success. Sometimes they are messy. Sometimes they fail. Sometimes the effort will cost you a lot of money. The point is, that's not necessarily a bad thing if what you're trying to do is build something new. (inc.com Sundar Pichai).",
                            
                            "First, you should define your value system. That is a set of principles that guide who you want to be as basis of your life mission. I codified my value system when I was young and modified it as time went by. For example, you should endeavor to lead, not follow. Another, you should do whatever it takes to succeed as long as it's not immoral or illegal.",
                                                                                              
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         "Being results-driven is a form of extrinsic motivation. This means that the motivation behind your behavior is either the seeking of a specific external reward (higher salary, social clout) or the avoidance of a specific external punishment (getting fired). It turns out, this orientation is terrible for long term productivity. The external thresholds against which we measure our worth are usually dictated by the environments we’re in. So, when we become. So focused on the goal and the precise steps needed to achieve it, we can fall into the trap of socially prescribed perfectionism (SPP). This can lead to depression, test anxiety, and decreased help-seeking. These re all unpleasant feelings, and what do we do to avoid these things? Procrastinate. When effort, not outcome, is rewarded, we are ore likely to take risks. That’s how innovation is born. When it’s not just about the destination, we care more about the journey. That’s because when we’re intrinsically motivated, we feel a sense of ownership over our work, connect deeply to its metaphysical meaning, brush up on relevant skills that make us more competent, and feel confident in the story we’re pushing for. (inc.com)",

                                                            
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         "'You have to encourage innovation. Companies become more conservative in decision making as you grow… be okay with failure and reward effort, not outcomes' - Sundar Pichai. Steve Jobs, although an effective leader and marketer would rarely acknowledge and congratulate his workers for great ideas. If you want to incentivize people to work hard and feel a sense of ownership and unity, you must reward their good ideas, acknowledge their idea, and give them some reward. This motivates them to continue doing similar things. When major goals are achieved, you should celebrate those moments with parties, gatherings, etc. If an idea is not so good, do not yell at the and make them feel stupid. Rather, explain what was wrong with the idea, and how it can become a good idea, or if there is no way to improve the idea, simply congratulate them for any good parts of it.",
                                                                                                                     
                                                                                                                                                                           "A Key characteristic of highly charismatic and effective leaders is admitting their mistakes. This demonstrates vulnerability and humility and makes you more likeable. Additionally, it creates a culture of responsibility and accountability in the organization.",
                                                                                                                                            "To succeed you need a clearly defined objective, commit to it, then laser focus on how to acheive it. You can never succeed if you do not even define success.",
                                                                                                    
