                            "You should always be willing to change your strategy, self-reflect, and thoroughly think through your actions to determine whether they are worth it. If not, you should give up on that idea. However, if you truly believe in an idea that you want to make a reality, you cannot just give up because it seems very difficult or nearly impossible. Real perseverance is battling even harder even in the face of almost certain failure. A true champion snatches victory from the jaws of defeat. The reason why we may end up cramming in work or running out of time is because we have too many important things due soon. In general, we have important things that are due soon, non-important things due soon, important things that are not due soon, and non-important things that aren't due soon. The key is to determine what's important to you, and to do the important things that aren't due soon ASAP. This way, you'd almost never have important things that are due soon. If you accomplish this, you'll never run out of time or find yourself cramming. This is the key to time management (paraphrase of Randy Pausch). ",
                            
                            "ALWAYS TRY TO PIVOT, CHANGE STRATEGY: However, sometimes, you cannot continue what you are pursuing. This may have been the entirely wrong thing to pursue. Some signs you should give up are that: You are not happy with the process anymore, Deep inside, you know it won't work out, You have let your goals and ambitions identify you, You think you will feel relieved when you give up,  Your life feels miserable.",
                                                                                              
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         "1. Write down your goals 2. Make your goals SMART It doesn’t matter if they’re personal goals or work goals. After writing down your goals, you need to make sure they’re SMART: Specific, Measurable, Attainable, Realistic, and Time-Oriented. The acronym SMART was created in 1981 when George T. Doran, a consultant and former Director of Corporate Planning for Washington Water Power Company, published a paper titled “There’s a S.M.A.R.T. Way to Write Management’s Goals and Objectives”. Since then, this system has gained worldwide popularity and is one of the most respected ways of setting goals. Thus, a SMART goal is: Specific: clear as water, unambiguous. Measurable: with specific criteria that assess its achievement. Achievable: it cannot be impossible to accomplish. Realistic: within reach and relevant to your life purpose. Time-Oriented: it needs a deadline. Although ideally, all goals should be SMART, the author explains that not all goals have to fulfill the 5 SMART criteria in the original document. Not everything is, for example, measurable. 3. Determine what you need to do to achieve them: Achieving your goals doesn’t depend only on your will. You need to spend time, sometimes money, have years of training, and even some help. So after you have set your goals, it’s time to ask yourself what you need to achieve them. Factors such as time, information, training, money, and support are some factors external to your motivation that you should consider. 4. Work your goals into your future plans: Now that you know exactly where you want to go and what you need to get there, it’s time to lay out a plan. Part of what makes your goals realistic is your ability to include them in your future plans and work toward them. So having a plan of action that helps you determine exactly how you will reach your goal is crucial. Be creative and look for solutions outside the box. 5. Evaluate and readjust your goals if need. Finally, our tip is to be flexible with your goals. Sometimes things happen, and not everything goes as we predict. So it’s important to have the permeability to realize when a goal is no longer realistic due to various factors and adjust it.",

                                                            
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         "Focus on your number one plan, goal, or 'dream': also have backups to help combat the fear of failure and to have a plan if things do not end up going your way.",
                                                                                                                     
                                                                                                                                                                           "Always celebrate successes of yourself and others however you want, as long as it's safe and legal.",
                                                                                                                                            "Many goals you have, or goals similar to yours, have already been achieved before. Therefore, learn the methodology and get advice from those who have already succeeded. If nothing like it has been done, learn from others, who have also done never before things.",
                                                                                                    
                                                                                                                                              "Not being willing to receive help is not a sign of strength, it is a sign of weakness. Be willing to accept help from others and ask people for help if it is their job to help you, or if you are really in need of help."

